<font color="#FF0000">MISS MANNERS SAYS: TSK TSK</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul 29 19:48:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
So Cook, you are now so frustrated and furious with me that I am just &quot;spatz&quot;, my, my, didn't yo momma teach you any manners? We can disagree and remain polite and civilized, can't we? I thought the military also taught &quot;class&quot; along with manhood and killing.  I will try and answer some of your more outrageous charges, but you are getting wilder and wilder. So I will ignore some of your wilder accusations.<br><br>
I registered for the draft on my 18th birthday, 1963 and I felt 10 feet tall and proud to be an American. I would have then, or now, gladly faught for my country if I felt my country was at risk or being attacked. It was neither in Viet Nam (and I refuse to discuss that point with you any farther - it is useless - been there, done that.)  You give me way too much power to control or sway the American people.  The fact is the silent majority got tired of body counts on the TV and finally brought enough pressure on the government to end the war.  <br><br>
Guess what Cook, I did not lose anything.  Sorry but you are wrong again when you say WE all lost.  I spent years counseling and education young men, and a few women, that it was their patriotic duty to resist a government that had gone wrong. That is the same principle that Patrick Henry subscribed too, and our Founding Fathers. Question Authority. ALWAYS!<br><br>
World War II and Germany is the example of what happens when dissent is silenced and the people do not question their government.  Thank God America is an open and free society, where it IS THE DUTY of the citizen to challenge and question his government on everything.  You (the military) were duped by our leaders and &quot;lost&quot; the war. I know that is a bitter pill for you and over simplistic. (enough said on this too in prior posts) It seems from your posts that you must be the biggest and badist soldier ever since Audie Murphy (the most decorated veteran in history), have one incredible memory for details that are 30 years old, or are writing fiction. I think probably the latter.<br><br>
You say you did not serve a second term because the war was being lost at home. What gives you the right to make that decision? You are/were a soldier, and must follow orders, no?  It was protestors such as ME that woke you up to the fact that the war wasn't as much being lost as it was wrong.<br>
Boy, that must stick in your craw. <br><br>
When you make absurd comparisons between emptying bedpans and saving a vietnamese child, I will not dignify illogical attacks like these with answers.  You really should try and control yourself and write a bit more calmly.  Did &quot;we&quot; abandon the Vietnamese to the communists?   First of all, I am not part of &quot;we&quot;, but I will attempt an answer. &quot;You&quot; abandoned them would be more accurate.  I tried to keep all of &quot;you&quot; from ever going there, remember?  <br><br>
Seems like sour grapes to me, Cook, hidden beneath words like valor and honor, lousy politicians and the failure of leadership.  Viet Nam was a mistake, a horrible mistake, made by many &quot;at the top&quot; and acted out by many at the bottom like you.  One of the clearest voices on this site, and someone I had some hot debates with, Tom Dier, has spoken this to you, but you don't listen to him either.<br>
It seems that you and Mr. Ramon, with his outhouse humor, are clearly the minority on this site Cook. Doesn't that tell you something?  Doesn't that tell you that you are wrong?  Wrong then, wrong now. Takes a man to admit that.<br><br>
The real tragedy of your &quot;thinking&quot; Cook, is that you can not see the difference between black and white, as I have told you before, so you can't see the 96 primary hues (colors) that exist between white (the absense of color) and black (the total of color). You lump all of the following together and I don't: draft resistors, draft evaders (canada bound), rich kids with connections, 4F-er's Legit, 4F-er's (phony), cowards, C.O.'s who became combat medic's (and I believe they are the biggest HERO's of all of you), C.O.'s who followed the law and the consitution (i.e. me), those that got drafted because they had nothing else going on in their lives, those who got &quot;enlisted&quot; by judges or courts, draftee's who did not go to Nam, and those who actually enlisted and wanted to go to Viet Nam.  That certainly is not all the sub groups, but enough to make my point. And you insist on lumping most of these into one group. Can you see that?<br><br>
For you to state that I &quot;got men killed&quot; is another one of your wild fantasies, and not worthy of retort.  Didn't you get the irony of my story to you about your &quot;capture&quot; of the Chinese Officier?  You were both foreigners fighting in a country that was not yours. BOTH. The Chinese had probably a better claim to be their than the USA did, like a common border and history.  Cook, you were the invader. Not the &quot;communists&quot;.  Jesus, will you start spewing the Domino Theory next?<br><br>
Had this world been an ideal world, and just, and instead of the French in Geneva splitting Viet Nam into two countries, and instead, had an election all over Viet Nam, can you imagine the results?  Uncle Ho would have swept the election. He was the most loved Vietnamese leader at the time. Not the phony CIA puppets that our country kept installing.  Now that is something I feel ashamed about. But I had no power to kill anyone, no power to control anyone, just my heart and guts to stand up to my country then, when it was acting like a global bully, or to you now, when I think you are a cyber-bully, and say to you again. You were wrong then. You are still wrong now.  And Frankly, Scarlet, I don't give a damn.  Meanwhile Cook, try and act like an Officer AND a Gentlemen, and be gracious in defeat.<br><br>
doc spatz<br><br>

